John Edwards: Language Skills are Necessary for Global Citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam results, which is only reinforced by individual and group success in sport, art, music and other community endeavors.
With more than 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the best service to their students and parents.
Independent schools strive to prepare their students for further and higher education, the career they have chosen and their place as global citizens.
As an educational center that can design and implement tailored school programs, we see that modern languages continue to be popular and desirable as an elective in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to a man in a language he understands, it will make him arrogant.
If you speak to him in his own language, it will strike him in the soul.”
This is a strong reminder that we can’t rely only on English when we want to build relationships and trust with people from other countries.
From this year’s recent exam results, we can see that languages outperform all other subjects with the highest success rate in independent schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who learned foreign languages achieved a higher score of “5+”.
Data collected from 74 SCIS schools showed that 72 percent of students achieved a higher "5+" rating in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who learned German, 69 percent of those who learned French and 63 percent of those who learned Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland support foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly acquire in the future.
Languages now, as an elective, are seen at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, engineering, and mathematics) in independent school programs, as well as elsewhere.
A 2014 OK Commission on Employment and Skills survey found that 17 percent of the reasons employers cited for failing to fill jobs were due to a lack of language skills.
Therefore, language skills are becoming increasingly compulsory in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more jobs requiring languages, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
No matter what career someone chooses, if they learn a second language, they will have a real advantage in the future by having such a lifelong skill.
The ability to communicate directly with people from foreign countries will automatically give the polyglot an advantage over the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 adults from OK in 2013, 75 percent could not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to speak, and French was the only language spoken by more than ten percent, i.e. 15 percent of people.
Therefore, investing in language teaching is now important for today’s children.
Having more languages, especially those in developing economies, will equip children with better chances of finding significant employment.
In Scotland, each school will differ according to the languages it teaches.
Several schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important in OK when looking into the future by 2020, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
No matter what your child’s interests are, there will always be a number of languages to choose from in independent schools, with professors who are specialists in this field.
Scottish independent schools are committed to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills needed to succeed, no matter what the future holds.
At the moment, it cannot be denied, in the global business environment, that languages will continue to be vital to the future of the country, so this has to be embodied in schools.
In fact, modern languages really need to be considered as “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to the young people of Scotland.
"Il faut bien le faire" (it must be done).
John Edwards is the director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
