New information about the red tide: Concentrations are decreasing in Pinelas, Manati and Sarasota
A recent report by the Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission shows a general decrease in red tide concentrations in parts of Tampa Bay area.
According to the Commission, conditions of uneven algae bloom have been observed in the Pinelas, Manati, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties, indicating a decrease in concentrations.
The red tide, a consequence of the bloom of red algae, stretches for about 130 miles along the coast from the northern Pinelas county to the southern Lee county.
Parts of the red tide can also be spotted about 10 miles off the coast of Hillsborough County, but the number is still smaller compared to last week.
Red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
Over the past week, the following concentrations have been observed in the nichoir and nichoir concentrations, the middle concentrations in or on the shore of Pinelas County, low to high concentrations on the shore of Hillsborough County, the concentrations common to high concentrations in or on the shore of Sarasota County, the concentrations in or on the shore of Saras County.
In the districts of Pinelas, Manati, Sarasota, Lee and Collier, cases of respiratory irritation continue to occur.
No cases of respiratory irritation have been reported in Northwest Florida in the past week.
